Performance monitoring, with v-m-stat, i-o-stat, and s-a-r.

When a system is slow, you need numbers rather than guesses, and three tools from the system-statistics package give you the whole picture. Install the package first, and you have v-m-stat, i-o-stat, and s-a-r at your disposal.

V-m-stat summarises see-pee-you, memory, swap, and disk activity on a single refreshing line. Run it with an interval, say every second, and watch the columns. A few of them are diagnostic gold. The r column counts runnable processes waiting for the processor; if it stays well above the number of cores, you are see-pee-you bound. The b column counts processes blocked waiting on input-output; if it is persistently above zero, you have a disk bottleneck. The s-i and s-o columns show swapping in and out, and any significant value there means swap thrashing and a need for more ram. The us and s-y columns split processor time between user code and the kernel; a high system figure often means a flood of system calls worth tracing. And the w-a column shows time spent waiting on input-output; high w-a points straight at the disk. One trap to remember: the very first line v-m-stat prints is an average since boot, so ignore it and read the lines that follow for what is happening right now.

The second tool, i-o-stat, drills into per-disk input-output detail, showing you which device is busy and how hard it is working, which is the natural next step once v-m-stat tells you the disk is the problem. And the third, s-a-r, the system activity reporter, can both show live figures and, very usefully, read back historical data that the package collects automatically, so you can answer the question, what was the system doing at three in the morning when it slowed down, long after the moment has passed.
